In article <1422@eouk9.eoe.co.uk> ahaley@eoe.co.uk (Andrew Haley)
writes:
>
> On the other hand, AFAIK PGP only uses a 128 bit hash to protect its
> key certificates, so an attack on the hash function would be easier
> than attacking the modulus.  Am I wrong about PGP in this respect?
> Does PGP use some extra method to protect its certificates?

The signature is also encrypted with the signer's secret key.  Thus,
you'd need to attack the modulus anyway.

